The extraction of nutmeg and mace essential oils by hydrodistillation method using Clevenger type apparatus and their oleoresins by Soxhlet extraction using ethanol as a solvent along with the testing of their antibacterial activity was done as per the methodology described in our previous communication10. Gas chromatography-mass spectrometry (GC-MS) analysis of nutmeg essential oil and mace oleoresin showing maximum antibacterial activity was also carried out with an Agilent 7890 A GC fitted with an HP-5MS column (30 m × 0.25 mm × 0.25 μm). Nitrogen, with a purity of 99.99%, served as the carrier gas at a flow rate of 1 ml/min. The test components were diluted in n-hexane (1 µl/ml) and 1.0 µl of this solution was injected into the column (1 µl/min) using a split mode ratio of 1:10. The injector temperature was set at 250 °C. The temperature programme for the oven was as follows: initially kept at 50°C for 2 min, then increased to 120 °C at the rate of 4 °C/min and maintained for 5 min, followed by rise to 230 °C (10 °C/min) for 10 min and finally raised to 280οC (20 °C/min) for 5 min where it was held constant for additional 10 min. Various MS parameters for the analysis were set on an Agilent MSD5975C MS detector with a detector voltage of 1.5 V, an ionization voltage of 70 eV and a mass range 45–600 amu. The identification of components was achieved by comparing their mass spectra with those in the NIST08 and WILEY8 libraries as well as National Building Specifications (NBS) database libraries (Table S1, S2 and Fig. S1, S2). The retention indices (RI) were calculated using a series of homologous n-alkane (C7-C40) under the same chromatographic conditions. To confirm the compounds, the RI values obtained were compared with those in the literature23 (Adam 2007) and were calculated using the formula:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
