The synergistic or combined interaction of isolated pure compounds and their most effective derivatives with standard antibiotic (streptomycin) was assessed by employing the checkerboard method30. This method involved diluting each treatment and the standard antibiotic in a 96-well microtiter plate, with two-fold dilutions ranging from MIC to 1/32 of MIC. Briefly, 50 µl of each treatment at MIC was combined with 50 µl of streptomycin at MIC with serial two-fold dilutions in Muller Hinton broth. Following this, a log-phase bacterial inoculum (100 µl) was inoculated to all the wells, and the plate was then kept in an incubator at 37 °C for 24 h. The MIC of each treatment alone, the standard antibiotic alone, and their combinations were recorded. The results were analyzed using the fractional inhibitory concentration index (FICI) as:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
