To the test tubes, 5 ml of nutrient broth was added, followed by the inoculation of 50 µl of microbial culture with an optical density (OD560) of 0.02 (equivalent to 106 CFU/ml). Subsequently, the most effective compound at its MIC as well as in combination with streptomycin was added. Only streptomycin-containing tubes served as the standard, while the tube without any compound acted as the control. The tubes were then kept undisturbed in the incubator for 48 h at 37 °C to allow for ring formation. Following incubation, the supernatant was carefully removed using a micro-pipette, and each tube was properly washed three times with distilled water to eliminate any unadhered or planktonic cells. The tubes were then air-dried for 30 min. Subsequently, 5 ml of a 1% aqueous solution of crystal violet dye was added to each tube and left for 15 min at room temperature. The dye solution was then discarded, and the tubes were gently washed three times with distilled water to remove excess stain. Next, 95% ethanol solution (5 ml) was added to each tube and kept in incubator for 15 min. Following this, the absorbance was noted at 570 nm using a double beam UV spectrophotometer (Perkin–Elmer 45). The SBF value was measured using the formula:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
